WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:14.480 --> 00:00:15.500
Good evening, Tucson.

00:00:15.500 --> 00:00:16.515
My name is Joaquin Ruiz.

00:00:16.515 --> 00:00:18.720
I'm the Dean of the
College of Science.

00:00:18.720 --> 00:00:21.434
And I thank you so much, all of
you, for coming here tonight.

00:00:25.070 --> 00:00:28.470
Many of you have been with
us for many of these lecture

00:00:28.470 --> 00:00:28.980
series.

00:00:28.980 --> 00:00:32.759
But I have to remind you that
today is the 10th anniversary

00:00:32.759 --> 00:00:35.310
of these lecture series.

00:00:35.310 --> 00:00:41.260
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:41.260 --> 00:00:44.890
And importantly, what everybody
should recognize in this room

00:00:44.890 --> 00:00:46.820
is that although I
think we've helped

00:00:46.820 --> 00:00:49.730
create some kind of
community through the lecture

00:00:49.730 --> 00:00:52.270
series, which we're very
proud of, all of you

00:00:52.270 --> 00:00:54.510
have also helped
create a community

00:00:54.510 --> 00:00:56.700
within the University of
Arizona, just by the way

00:00:56.700 --> 00:00:59.870
that we create these lectures.

00:00:59.870 --> 00:01:02.960
Just to give you a sense
of how it all works out,

00:01:02.960 --> 00:01:05.349
there's a little group
that sits down one day.

00:01:05.349 --> 00:01:08.160
And they say OK, what's
the next lecture series?

00:01:08.160 --> 00:01:10.700
My god, I don't know, we're
running out of themes.

00:01:10.700 --> 00:01:12.850
And somebody will come
up with a theme that

00:01:12.850 --> 00:01:14.650
sounds like it's reasonable.

00:01:14.650 --> 00:01:19.310
And then we pick up our
Rolodex, and we call faculty

00:01:19.310 --> 00:01:22.750
from the university to say
will you give a lecture.

00:01:22.750 --> 00:01:25.290
And then they'll get
together, and they themselves

00:01:25.290 --> 00:01:28.150
create the lecture
series as you know it.

00:01:28.150 --> 00:01:31.590
And if I could do anything that
would be truly extraordinary

00:01:31.590 --> 00:01:36.330
is to be able to film the deep
conversations of the speakers

00:01:36.330 --> 00:01:39.350
as they're creating the
lecture series for you.

00:01:39.350 --> 00:01:40.920
So they are the
ones that deserve

00:01:40.920 --> 00:01:42.700
a great round of applause.

00:01:42.700 --> 00:01:46.690
Because all we do is come up
with a theme and sort of duck

00:01:46.690 --> 00:01:49.610
after that.

00:01:49.610 --> 00:01:56.530
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:56.530 --> 00:02:00.160
Because this is the
10th anniversary,

00:02:00.160 --> 00:02:03.770
we felt that it had to be
something that was truly unique

00:02:03.770 --> 00:02:05.410
and that would be memorable.

00:02:05.410 --> 00:02:08.009
And of course, we've had many
memorable and unique lecture

00:02:08.009 --> 00:02:08.570
series.

00:02:08.570 --> 00:02:11.990
We've had evolution
of the brain.

00:02:11.990 --> 00:02:13.200
We've had cosmology.

00:02:13.200 --> 00:02:15.070
We've had genomics.

00:02:15.070 --> 00:02:18.860
Each one of those full of
mystery and full of things

00:02:18.860 --> 00:02:20.040
we don't know.

00:02:20.040 --> 00:02:24.930
And the hope of all of
us in the lectures and me

00:02:24.930 --> 00:02:28.560
is that by the time you
hear all these lectures,

00:02:28.560 --> 00:02:30.180
you know about as
much as everybody

00:02:30.180 --> 00:02:31.690
that's giving the lectures.

00:02:31.690 --> 00:02:34.190
Perhaps without the
mathematics and all

00:02:34.190 --> 00:02:35.770
these other little things.

00:02:35.770 --> 00:02:38.590
But that you understand
all the grand challenges

00:02:38.590 --> 00:02:42.400
and that you really sort of
get a sense of what we know.

00:02:42.400 --> 00:02:43.870
I hope we're good at that.

00:02:43.870 --> 00:02:47.370
I hope that we give you
lectures that stretch you,

00:02:47.370 --> 00:02:48.950
that don't bore you.

00:02:48.950 --> 00:02:51.810
And that in the end,
spark your imagination

00:02:51.810 --> 00:02:55.500
about what amazing things are
being discovered by all of us.

00:02:55.500 --> 00:02:59.210
This lecture series is
on life in the universe.

00:02:59.210 --> 00:03:02.630
What could be more
stretching than that?

00:03:02.630 --> 00:03:03.380
Are we alone?

00:03:03.380 --> 00:03:04.080
Are we not?

00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:07.880
What does that mean
in a cosmological way?

00:03:07.880 --> 00:03:10.380
What does that mean
in a biological way?

00:03:10.380 --> 00:03:13.960
And we have for you what I think
is an extraordinary lecture

00:03:13.960 --> 00:03:14.920
series.

00:03:14.920 --> 00:03:16.810
It has a couple of biologists.

00:03:16.810 --> 00:03:19.800
I will tell you because,
in fact, what we

00:03:19.800 --> 00:03:21.600
are is planet-centric.

00:03:21.600 --> 00:03:23.480
And what is it
that we're actually

00:03:23.480 --> 00:03:25.320
looking for in other planets?

00:03:25.320 --> 00:03:28.880
What do we understand about
life in our own planet?

00:03:28.880 --> 00:03:31.140
And then the rest
of the speakers

00:03:31.140 --> 00:03:34.450
will spend their time
trying to convince you

00:03:34.450 --> 00:03:37.070
that the science that they're
doing is worth something.

00:03:37.070 --> 00:03:40.240
And that they know what
they're looking for.

00:03:40.240 --> 00:03:44.510
And that maybe they
will find something.

00:03:44.510 --> 00:03:49.320
Today's lecture is
perhaps the key lecture

00:03:49.320 --> 00:03:51.180
in the whole lecture series.

00:03:51.180 --> 00:03:56.040
Because Guy Consolmagno, brother
Guy, is going to try to define

00:03:56.040 --> 00:03:57.790
what life is.

00:03:57.790 --> 00:04:00.514
And if you're trying to find
something somewhere else,

00:04:00.514 --> 00:04:01.930
you might as well
know what you're

00:04:01.930 --> 00:04:04.950
trying to find if
you're going to find it.

00:04:04.950 --> 00:04:07.480
So that's what this
lecture is about.

